1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 {In a recent interview
Grishchuk admitted that this gambit is for him like a red cloth to a bull - he
is unable to resist it. This game shows he has a good reason for this - his
excellent understanding of the resulting tense positions.} dxc4 7. e4 g5 8. Bg3
b5 9. Ne5 {Although this N sortie is typical for the whole line, White more
often chooses a different move order. More popular is the developing} (9. Be2
Bb7 {and now White has a choice - the two main alternatives are} 10. O-O ({or} 
10. h4 g4 11. Ne5 h5 12. O-O Nbd7 {which transposes into the game.}) 10... Nbd7
11. Ne5 Bg7 {, now} 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Bd6 a6 $44 {~~ is the second topical
possibility (see my notes in CBM 124 to;Radjabov,T (2751)-Aronian,L (2763)/
Sofia MTel Masters 4th 2008 (3)/1/2-1/2}) 9... h5 $5 {This move has currently
the best reputation.} ({In an earlier game between the same opponents,
Karjakin went for} 9... Bb7 10. h4 Rg8 (10... g4 11. Nxg4 Nbd7 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6
13. Qf3 Rg8 14. Be2 a6 15. Rd1 Nd7 16. O-O Qf6 17. Qe3 O-O-O 18. b3 cxb3 19.
axb3 Be7 20. Rc1 $16 {Black hasn't managed to create sufficient <=> and his
vulnerable K will soon become a direct target.} Qh8 21. Bh2 Qg7 22. Bf3 e5 23.
Nd5 Bd6 24. Qc3 Rde8 25. Qa5 Re6 26. Rxc6+ $1 Bxc6 27. Rc1 Nb8 28. Rxc6+ $1
Nxc6 29. Qxa6+ $18 {->, Gelfand,B (2723)-Alekseev,E (2711)/RUS-chT Dagomys/
2008/}) 11. hxg5 hxg5 {There seems to be more space for White's improvements
after} 12. Qf3 $5 ({This line seems very risky for Black, but} 12. Nxf7 {isn't
sufficient for an advantage after} Kxf7 13. e5 Nd5 14. Rh7+ Bg7 15. Qh5+ Kf8
16. Qf3+ (16. Ne4 Qa5+ 17. Kd1 Qa4+ 18. Kc1 Nb4 19. Qf3+ Ke8 20. Nd6+ Kd8 21.
Qf6+ Kc7 22. Ne8+ Kb6 23. Qd8+ Ka6 24. Nc7+ Ka5 25. Ne8+ {1/2, Estremera Panos,
S (2394)-Perez Candelario,M (2537)/La Massana/2008/ is another, more
attractive perpetual.}) 16... Ke8 17. Qh5+ {1/2, Grischuk,A (2716)-Karjakin,S 
(2732)/Baku/2008/}) 12... Qe7 13. O-O-O Nbd7 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. e5 O-O-O 16. Ne4
c5 17. d5 Qe8 18. Qg4 (18. d6 f5 19. exf6 Qg6 20. Re1 $13 {/+/=}) 18... Bxd5
19. Rh7 Be7 20. Rxd5 exd5 21. e6 f5 22. Qxf5 dxe4 23. Qxe4 Nb6 24. Rxe7 Rd1+
25. Kxd1 Qxe7 26. Be2 (26. Qc6+ $5 Kd8 27. Be2 $36) 26... Qb7 27. Qe3 Qd5+ 28.
Kc1 Rh8 29. e7 Rh1+ 30. Kc2 Qf5+ 31. Kd2 Qd7+ 32. Kc2 Qf5+ 33. Kd2 Qd7+ 34. Kc2
Qf5+ {1/2, Sargissian,G (2676)-Perez Candelario,M (2537)/Merida/2008/}) ({
Anand also prefered the text-move after the following experience:} 9... Bg7
$143 $6 10. h4 Nfd7 (10... g4 11. Nxg4 Nxg4 12. Qxg4 Qxd4 13. Rd1 $44) 11. hxg5
hxg5 12. Rxh8+ Bxh8 13. Qh5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Nxe5 15. Qh8+ Kd7 16. Qxe5 Bb7 17.
O-O-O Kc8 18. Qg7 Qe7 19. e5 Nd7 20. Ne4 $36 {Kasimdzhanov,R (2683)-Anand,V 
(2792)/Mainz rpd/2007/}) {The best, as it wins a tempo.} 10. h4 (10. f3 $143 h4
11. Bf2 Bb7 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. O-O e5 15. a4 a6 16. d5 Rh6 17. dxc6
Bxc6 18. axb5 axb5 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 20. Qc1 Rg6 21. Rd1 Bc5 $15 {/-/+,Carlsen,M 
(2733)-Anand,V (2799)/Morelia/2008/}) 10... g4 $8 11. Be2 {Black is behind in
development and for the time being must keep the position closed.} ({The same
goes here for White, weaker is} 11. f3 Rg8 $5 $132 {<->g[%cal Gg8g1]}) 11...
Bb7 {In this line Black should very carefully consider the disruption of his
<< P-phalanx - it's one of his main positional trumps.} ({However, in this
concrete position the rare} 11... b4 $5 {deserves attention:} 12. Na4 Nxe4 13.
Bxc4 Nxg3 14. fxg3 Nd7 (14... Bg7 $5 {is also playable and perhaps stronger:}
15. Nc5 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Qxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Nd7 18. Nxd7 Bxd7 19. Ba6 Rb8 20. Rc1 Ke7
21. Rf1 Rb6 22. Bc4 c5 23. Be2 Rc8 $15 {Amura,C (2355)-Delgado Crespo,M (2298)/
San Felipe/1999/}) 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. O-O Bb7 (16... Bg7 $5 $15) 17. Qe2 Bg7 18.
Rad1 Qe7 19. Nc5 Rh6 20. Kh2 Rd8 21. Qe4 Rd6 22. a3 bxa3 23. bxa3 Bc8 24. Qe3
Rd8 $13 {Maletin,P (2545)-Kobalia,M (2618)/RUS-ch qual Novokuznetsk/2008/}) 12.
O-O (12. f3 Nbd7 13. fxg4 hxg4 14. O-O Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Nd7 $1 16. Bxh8 Qxh4 17.
